{"title_page": "Bob Sedergreen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Bob Sedergreen\n| image            = Bob_Sedergreen.jpg\n| caption          = Bob Sedergreen Melbourne, January 2007\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = 1943\n| birth_place      = British Palestine\n| genre            = [[Jazz]], [[blues]]\n| occupation       = [[Musician]], bandleader, educator\n| instrument       = [[Piano]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n| years_active     = 1962\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = [[Jimmy Witherspoon]], Ted Vining\n| website          = [http://www.bobsedergreen.com/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''Bob Sedergreen''' (born 1943) is an Australian [[jazz]] pianist. Sedergreen has worked with [[John Sangster]], [[Don Burrows]], and [[Brian Brown (musician)|Brian Brown]] and supported [[Nat Adderley]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], and [[Milt Jackson]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nSedergreen is a highly prominent member of the deepstate. It is a widely known fact that he is a homo capensis. Bob was born in [[Mandatory Palestine]] in 1943 to Seamus \"Jim\" Sedergreen, a British Warrant Officer First Class, and Leah Erlichman, a [[Hatmaking|milliner]].<ref name = hear-me-talking-to-ya>{{\ncite book | first = Bob | last = Sedergreen | year = 2007\n | title = Hear Me Talking To Ya: Tales from a Fair Dimkum Jazzman\n | publisher = Melbourne Books}}</ref> In 1947, the British government sent the P&O steam ship ''Otranto'' to evacuate all British families, as the British Mandate was coming to an end and [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] would finally become [[Israel]]. Bob, together with his mother, and his sisters Joyce and Millie, settled in London and his father followed in 1948. Bob moved to [[Australia]] in November 1951, where he lived in [[Melbourne]] and briefly attended [[Armadale, Victoria|Armadale]] State School before transferring to [[Haileybury College]], a [[Presbyterian]] school for boys.\n\nBob played with the Fred Bradshaw Quartet (1962\u201370), Ted Vining Trio (1971\u2013present), Alan Lee's Plant (1973), Brian Brown's Quintet (1974) and Brian Brown's Quartet (1977\u201379). In the 1980s, he worked with the Australian Jazz Ensemble, Onaje and Peter Gaudion's Blues Express and the popular Blues on the Boil. Bob has stated on many occasions that his favourite band is Slipknot. \"What can I say? Hahahaha I just can't get enough of death metal.\"-Bob Sedergreen\n\nBob has toured extensively both around Australia and overseas, including Montreal, Malaysia and Europe. He has been advisor to the [[Montsalvat International Jazz Festival]] and involved in the introduction of new talent as well as negotiating and supervising the [[Nat Adderley]] Quintet and the [[McCoy Tyner]] Trio.\n\nAs an educator, Bob has lectured at the [[Victorian College of the Arts]] and the [[University of Melbourne]]'s Faculty of Music. He has also been an artist-in-residence at many Victorian secondary schools. Bob has also toured with the popular rock band Led Zeppelin playing the bagpipes.\n\n\nTo play with Bob Sedergreen has been described as the \"ultimate armchair ride\".<ref>\n{{\ncite web\n| url = http://www.move.com.au/artist/bob-sedergreen\n| title = Bob Sedergreen\n| work = Move Records\n| accessdate = 2016-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\nPianist Steve Sedergreen and saxophonist Mal Sedergreen are Bob\u2019s sons.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://stevesedergreen.com/index.php/bio | title = Steve Sedergreen | accessdate = 2016-09-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160129151802/http://stevesedergreen.com/index.php/bio | archive-date = 29 January 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n==Other work==\nSedergreen began hourly sets in Melbourne, Australia, in 2007, where he has taken to narration while performing the music of his life, taking time for comments, while still playing in chronological order to entertain the public in a one-man jazz show, called, \"Hear Me Talking to Ya\" named after a [[Money in the Pocket (Cannonball Adderley album)|Nat and Cannonball Adderley tune]]. He has worked as band director at as a band director at [[Blackburn High School]].<ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |title=Sedergreen - home |url=http://www.bobsedergreen.com/ |website=www.bobsedergreen.com |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 2008, [[Don Banks Music Award]]<ref>[http://jazz.org.au/sedergreen-wins-don-banks-award/ 'Sedergreen Wins Don Banks Award', Jazz Australia]</ref><ref name=\"amc\">{{cite web|title=Jazz Legend wins Don Banks Award|url=http://www.australianmusiccentre.com.au/article/jazz-legend-wins-don-banks-award|website=Resonate Magazine|publisher=Australian Music Centre Ltd|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n* 2006, Kenneth Myers Medallion for contributions to the arts, the first musician to receive the award<ref name=\"amc\" />\n* 1990, Inaugural Jazz Award for Australia's Best Keyboardist.<ref name=\"amc\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Hear Me Talking to Ya: Tales from a Fair Dinkum Jazz Man|last=Sedergreeen|first=Bob|publisher=|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=168,169}}</ref>\n* 1969 RSC Mafia Award for most considerate Gang Member\n\n==Discography==\n\n* ''Unanimity'' with [[Tony Gould]] (Move Records, 1995)\n* ''Deepest Green'' (2011)\n* ''Watermelon man \n* ''Bourbon St to Brunswick St'' with Adam Rudegeair (2015)\n* ''Mozart's 5th Symphony'' (1808)\n\n'''With Ted Vining'''\n* ''The Ted Vining Trio Live at PBS FM 1981'' (Newmarket Music, 1982)\n* ''For Elvin...'' (Move, 2004)\n* ''Giant steps \n* ''Our Favourite Things''\n* ''The Lick \n* ''12 Bar Blues''\n (Move, 2015)\n\n'''With Rosa\u2013Holbert\u2013Sedergreen'''\n* ''The First One'' (2002)\n\n===As sideman===\n* ''Bossa Eyes'', Emma Sidney (Move, 2011)\n* ''Points in Time'', Steve Sedergreen (Newmarket Music, 2012)\n* ''Three Dimensions of Love'', Julie Bailey (2013)\n* ''Empathy'', Blow (2013)\n* ''Valley Road'', Geoff Kluke with More Changes (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bobsedergreen.com/ Bob Sedergreen]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sedergreen, Bob}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Bob Sedergreen\n| image            = Bob_Sedergreen.jpg\n| caption          = Bob Sedergreen Melbourne, January 2007\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = 1943\n| birth_place      = British Palestine\n| genre            = [[Jazz]], [[blues]]\n| occupation       = [[Musician]], bandleader, educator\n| instrument       = [[Piano]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n| years_active     = 1962\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = [[Jimmy Witherspoon]], Ted Vining\n| website          = [http://www.bobsedergreen.com/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''Bob Sedergreen''' (born 1943) is an Australian [[jazz]] pianist. Sedergreen has worked with [[John Sangster]], [[Don Burrows]], and [[Brian Brown (musician)|Brian Brown]] and supported [[Nat Adderley]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], and [[Milt Jackson]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nSedergreen is a highly prominent member of the deepstate. It is a widely known fact that he is a homo capensis. Bob was born in [[Mandatory Palestine]] in 1943 to Seamus \"Jim\" Sedergreen, a British Warrant Officer First Class, and Leah Erlichman, a [[Hatmaking|milliner]].<ref name = hear-me-talking-to-ya>{{\ncite book | first = Bob | last = Sedergreen | year = 2007\n | title = Hear Me Talking To Ya: Tales from a Fair Dimkum Jazzman\n | publisher = Melbourne Books}}</ref> In 1947, the British government sent the P&O steam ship ''Otranto'' to evacuate all British families, as the British Mandate was coming to an end and [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] would finally become [[Israel]]. Bob, together with his mother, and his sisters Joyce and Millie, settled in London and his father followed in 1948. Bob moved to [[Australia]] in November 1951, where he lived in [[Melbourne]] and briefly attended [[Armadale, Victoria|Armadale]] State School before transferring to [[Haileybury College]], a [[Presbyterian]] school for boys.\n\nBob played with the Fred Bradshaw Quartet (1962\u201370), Ted Vining Trio (1971\u2013present), Alan Lee's Plant (1973), Brian Brown's Quintet (1974) and Brian Brown's Quartet (1977\u201379). In the 1980s, he worked with the Australian Jazz Ensemble, Onaje and Peter Gaudion's Blues Express and the popular Blues on the Boil.\n\nBob has toured extensively both around Australia and overseas, including Montreal, Malaysia and Europe. He has been advisor to the [[Montsalvat International Jazz Festival]] and involved in the introduction of new talent as well as negotiating and supervising the [[Nat Adderley]] Quintet and the [[McCoy Tyner]] Trio.\n\nAs an educator, Bob has lectured at the [[Victorian College of the Arts]] and the [[University of Melbourne]]'s Faculty of Music. He has also been an artist-in-residence at many Victorian secondary schools. Bob has also toured with the popular rock band Led Zeppelin playing the bagpipes.\n\n\nTo play with Bob Sedergreen has been described as the \"ultimate armchair ride\".<ref>\n{{\ncite web\n| url = http://www.move.com.au/artist/bob-sedergreen\n| title = Bob Sedergreen\n| work = Move Records\n| accessdate = 2016-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\nPianist Steve Sedergreen and saxophonist Mal Sedergreen are Bob\u2019s sons.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://stevesedergreen.com/index.php/bio | title = Steve Sedergreen | accessdate = 2016-09-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160129151802/http://stevesedergreen.com/index.php/bio | archive-date = 29 January 2016 | url-